Jonatan on 2026-06-19 at ~23:40: That's mostly good, and the lighting is beginning to look really nice. Let's go to the next iteration. Before doing it let me notice, that you complained about not having a way to render the page. But I think that problem was already solved by you in another session. And I told you before to install a package system-wide so that I can use it too if you needed. Maybe you were able to render then because you installed something but now you're not able to access that install? Maybe I'm wrong, but something like that is what I suspect happened. The first thing about the string on the annulus is that it lags behind the illumination of the annulus. I'm starting to think that integrating the message with the logo could be a good idea. If that is possible. To make the logo react in synchrony with the text. If you find a better way that's ok, but the way I would do it would be to literally write the string onto the logo. You already know how to transform a horizontal band into an arc of the logo's annulus, so actually writing the message in the SVG should be doable. The string could be written with a more simple traces. I mean that the letters' shape as they currently are involve a lot of small stroke decorations, and that a more straightforward trace would be ok too. I imagine the fonts as if the letters of the string were carved with a knife just to give you an idea. Once you have the modified logo, I would design the lighting of the annulus around an uniform-arc partition idea. Of dividing the angular space in a uniform a0=0, a1=2pi/360,a2=2*2ip/360,...,a360=2pi-2pi/360. Just eyeballed the 360 because of one-degree idea. This partition can hold illuminance values of both the outside and the inside boundary. Imagine splitting up the annulus in two concentric circumferences of equal width, so as to divide them. Then imagine spliting each of the two resulting annulus in sections but now in the angular space instead of the radial one. If we start at 0 and counterclockwise in increments of 2pi/360, then we have 360 pieces, for each part of the boundary. So now that we have mapped the logo's annulus to this two sequences, we are going to use them to store changing illumination values as the page scrolls up or down. The outer part of the annulus has to be aware of the illumination that it reads from outside points. Since each piece corresponds to a small arc, you should just calculate the total illumination received on those two points and average out to get a value. Notice that this involves, at beginning and each time the view scrolls, calculating the illumination value at the angular-wise uniform sequence of points that start at the outer boundary of the annulus, and rotate anticlockwise 2pi/360 to get to the next point. Once we have the full 360 points we neet to calculate their illuminance levels, coming from the outside points. I was still thinking on the midpoint idea but I changed my mind; just use the value of the left end of the arc piece instead of averaging since the effect won't be even close to be noticeable. Once You have this, a similar technique to what I believe the code to entail should be enough to actually apply the illumination sequence onto the illumination of the outer half of the annulus. I think the lighting of the annulus and the logo as it is right now it really good, so it might be a good idea to render and capture how does it look, the logo lighting, and the inner annulus and the outer annulus. You might want to ultrathink for this. I don't know if this will be fighting the way the site gets rendered. I think the current source code tries to do some things against the flow that the browser writes in, and that that might be what is causing the lagging in the string's lighting. In the way I laid out you don't need to worry about an overly sampled text that acts independently of the annulus and is probably computated separately. Taking into account that we know exactly the position of the points, the most efficient way to do the lighting seems to me to add its contribution to the annulus, from the first little arc that it sees until the last. Recall that here the endpoints of this interval you can fetch as theta\pm arccos(r+/r), where r and theta are the polar coordinates of the illuminating point with respect to the center of the exterior boundary. Notice that r+ refers to the outer radius of the annulus. I want you to draw lines again from the illuminating exterior points to their contact points on the outer boundary. The formula above gives the angular coodinate of those, and their radius is r+. And a similar thing should be done for the interior half annulus, but this time there's no restriction on the angular segment that becomes active due to an illuminating point, since points inside light up the whole annulus's inside. Just note that, if it doesn't fight the rendering, maybe starting the refresh of the page scrolls with the exterior illuminating points that are closer to the center of the logo, that could be a good idea, since those are the ones that account for most of the variation of illumination and so the most impactful on perception. That for the outer boundary of the annulus. For the interior boundary you should start with the points that are further from the origin, as they are the ones that are closer to the inner boundary of the annulus. Another idea that could be helpful maybe is to choose a coarser rasterization of the bands in fewer resolution than 360. In principle that could cause some trouble and separating artifacts start to emerge in between the little arcs, but a difussion effect with low filter size of the whole annulus (or, equivalently, the pieces of if that changed) should be a sensible solution. To guide the lighting effect you could use a different illumination pattern from each illumination level, and have the arc display that pattern. The inside boundary of the annulus could use the same pattern display, only flipped to face the interior of the annulus. I think it will be here that you will need to have the capacity to render the website, and take captures of a handful of cases of illumination from a single outside point placed at a handful of sensible different distances. Say of a point just to the right of the logo, then another one a word's distance to the left, then another, and so up to say 7 different distances, that span evenly out from "very close to the outside boundary" to "almost where it is not noticeable". That gives a pattern for the shape of the effect. Or, viewed numerically, dictates how the illumination of the little arc is distributed as cut up according to their radii. It just gives depth to an other wise flat illuminance value. And the point of this is that, because of radial symmetry, the system is additive. Meaning that if p0 denotes the arc pattern of a completely dark little arc, and p12 the arc pattern of a completelly illuminated arc of the outer boundary, and if the illumination value on that arc was 3.22 (and so p3 was on), then a contribution onto that little arc of 2.91, then the pattern that arc should update to is the one that you would play at 3.22+2.91=6.13 (p6). A similar thing of course should go for the inside, with obvious modifications. Let's see what you can do. Please install (for wide use) if you need something to visualize the website with the prearranged setting above, I think it will go along way in guiding you towards replicating the current lighting. Didn't explicitly say it, but notice that the arcs that the string message falls on would need a different treatment. I think that here a mask for letters is warranted instead of the little arc approach. I think that individual letters sharing the same illumination value as the one little arc that falls on the midpoint of the region that the letter covers is fine. This way a whole letter could just have one illumination value, that corresponds to a different intensity of its lighting. At the minimum of 0 not visible, then increase in multiples of 1 until the maximum of 13, which would correspond to a maximally lit up letter. I'm just realizing that the step about carving the string onto the logo is probably not necessary but, except that oversight on my part, I think this is the way to make the text dependent on the lighting of the annulus (and thus avoid the lag). Please take as much time as you need, this is a big iteration. I think that what I laid out takes advantage of the most important aspects to take into account from the symmetry of the problem, but there might be other ways to improve on the rendering or the responsiveness of the page. So try modified approaches if mine you find lackign in the testing against the captured lighting samples. And do stop and ask if you didn't understand something I said, or if you are confident that some other way to tackle the situation would be better. Otherwise, good luck!

